review_blob: A good swedish version of an english BW! The taste is not overly malty or hoppy, but has a lot of soil, plums, portwine and raisins in it. This one was fresh, and not the best BW Ive had, but I have great hopes of it developing in a positive direction when cellared.
A good sour/fruit-lambic kind of beer. The cuve was better, but this still is a solid pick. The fruity character comes out pretty well, and the result is a relatively complex and drinkable brew.

Im kind of tired of these big, coffee-infused imperial stouts, but I gotta admit that this one is a great take on the style. Its better than, say, Mikkellers BGBW and Peche Mortel, hands down. Taste contains a great deal of dark chocolate, snuff, coffee, roasted malts and liquorish, without becoming too overwhelming or unbalanced. A great sipper if one is in the mood for this kind of beer.
I know I shouldnt like this, but I kind of do. It cant compete with real lambics or other sours, but i like the mellow tones of cherries and almond, and the sweetness that comes with it.

Now this is a great looking brew. A full, red color, like they used more of the raspberries than in other, similar fruit-lambics. Acidity is at an acceptable level. Well-balanced, fruity and very enjoyable!

I enjoyed this brew very much! The lack of carbonation felt strange at first, but the flavors that came out when it warmed up a bit more than made up for that. The nose is very specific; I bet I could single this out as a Cantillon brew at a blind tasting by the aroma alone! Taste contains a lot of of apples, green currant-berries, oak, yeast and the specific cantillon-taste that resembles blue cheese, hay and something else... Very complex, but not overly sour, unlike some other lambics from cantillon.

A nose of crme brulee, coffee, sweetness (initially pleasent...) and then an overwhelming chemical taste that reminds me of sour milk. Taste is of mashmellows and punsch. The chemical character that comes out half-way through makes this the worst beer Ive ever had.

A nose of tobacco, whiskey, smoked sausage, leather and vanilla. Taste is of leather, vanilla, smoke and fertilizer. An interesting but very extreme brew. Its very unique, but the mix of leathery smoke and sweetness doesnt really do it do me.

A nose of strawberries, "rulltrta", metal, grape and lemon. Taste is of citrus, dandelion, anis, iron and grass. It has a little acidity to it, and finish is bitter and salty in a well-balanced way. Very drinkable and elegant for an APA.
beer_name: Great Divide Fresh Hop Pale Ale

beer_brewer_name: Brouwerij der Trappistenabdij De Achelse Kluis
review_blob: A nose of alcohol, marzipan, lemons and yeast. Taste is of red wine, grape, iron, pears and amaretto.Its yeasty and dry, and somewhat complex. Not bad, but not my pick for a belgian strong either.

A sweet nose of cherries, oak, yeast and red wine. The taste brings out basically the same flavors. Its a bit acidic at first, but then it mellows out, leaving only a minty aftertaste. I would like a bit more sweetness and/or sourness and a little complexity. Drinkable but not fantastic. With the yeast in the glass, the beer gets better, though.

A nose of chocolate, black currant, alcohol and yeast. Taste is of red wine, raspberries, cherries and dried, fermented fruit. Its acidic, and the finish is a bit dry, and has a pinch of alcohol in it. Halfway through the taste, a kick-ass complex bitterness comes out and dominates. Its not a hoppy, flowery bitterness, but rather a "green", raw, plant-like bitterness. Like chewing on the white stuff between a grapefruits pulp and peel.
This brew is surprisingly tart and sour! Strange, as it tasted more like a regular belgian strong fresh, just 6 months ago. Back then it was just average. Now its a masterpiece truly worthy of its hype. Its amazingly complex, and it sure beats all the belgian strongs, lambics and sours that has a rating below 4 here on ratebeer imo. Just dont have it fresh. Its really not the same beer. I hope that explains the low rating its gotten.

A good belgian IS? I gotta admit I was a bit skeptical, even though I like other beers from Struise, mainly due to the fact that the foam resembled that of the Hercule IS that I didnt find too exciting. The aroma was wonderful though, if only a bit sharp - Chocolate, liquorish and orange peel. The taste is subtle at first, and then the complex flavors creep up on you. Rum raisins, apples, calvados, red wine, chocolate and just a touch of alcohol in the finish. Its elegant, fruity, and a bit acidic. An absolutely awesome beer! Works great together with Lindts chocolate with seasalt.

A nose of tobacco, liquorish and raw coffee. The note of raw coffee continues to dominate i the taste as well, but I can also discern a bit of green apples, cherries, snuff and chocolate. A bit too acidic though. I thought this to be a foreign stout, mainly due to the low alcohol and bitterness. If it really does classify as an IS, its not by much.

A typical brit. No experiments and no big sensations in taste, but on the upside its well balanced and pretty drinkable.

A nose of soil, chocolate, aceton and glue. Taste is of raw coffee, liquorish, soil and glue. Finish is bitter and sharp. I didnt really care for this one, and Im perplexed to see the high rating. Maybe mine were too fresh with only 2 months since being tapped? The glueish smell and taste reminds me of certain quads and Fullers vintage - In all those beers it is a signum of a beer being opened too early, a beer that has true aging potential. Maybe this goes for my ex. of Dark Force as well?
A nose of bread, citrus and yeast. Taste is of orange and iron. Finish is a bit bitter, but it doesnt linger. I cant really understand the "hype" surrounding this beer in the swedish beer-blogs.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: A nose of vanilla, tobacco, alcohol and funk. Taste is of grass, metal, vanilla, coffee and oak. Finish is a bit "green", acidic and dry. A strange but very enjoyable experience.
A fruity nose of elderflowers, pineapple, lemon and basil. Taste contains grape, dandelion and basil. Finish is bitter and alcoholic. Id like more fruity notes and less bitterness.

A wonderful nose that bears similarities to westvleteren is its nice composition between cookies, dough and marzipan. Some plums, yeast and raisins are also present. Taste isnt as convincing; Apples, dough, dried fruit and a ton of amaretto. Finish is alcoholic and a bit bitter. This wasnt too great fresh, but the marzipan in scent and taste promises nice development while cellared. Ill wait and see.
A dusty nose of coffee, vanilla, metal and alcohol. Taste is of oak, raw coffee, liquorish and vanilla. The finish has a good balance between the salty and the bitter. Overall: A good barrel aged IS.

A fresh nose of blood orange and apples. Taste is of wood, red currant and red grapes. Finish is bone dry. The fruity character comes out very well and its balanced with the acid. Almost no funk, which is a bit unusual. Lambics are often very acidic and a bit soapy, but not this one. It could be the best one Ive had in this style.
A nose of grape, lemon and alcohol. Taste is of grape, grass, metal and cucumber. Finish is bitter and alcoholic. This brew was so so.
A nose of pinewood, juniper berries and funk. Taste is of yeast, sugars, cheese, toffee and a lot of funk. This didnt really do it for me.
A nose of hops and citrus. Taste is of iron and funk.Finish is "rancid" and dry. Boring and hopeless.
A nose of iron, lemon and top-fermenting yeast. The taste brings out the same flavors. Finish is quite good, and keeps this brew from being utterly and totally uninteresting.
A nose of raspberries, elderflower and sugars. Taste is of apples and peach. Its acidic and dry. A strange brew. Not too enjoyable.
UPDATED: DEC 13, 2009

A nose of pears, amaretto and sugars. Taste is of pears, banana, almonds, marzipan and quite a bit of alcohol. A strange brew. Not complex and very unbalanced. A bad bottle? I will rerate if I get the chance.

Bottle from 2008. A nose of jam, strawberries, toffee, oak and alcohol. Taste is of strawberries, cookie, soil and a lot of funk, almost too much. Finish is salty and bitter and has a bit of alcohol in it. A solid BW.

A nose of cherries, almonds and soap. Taste is of cherries, grass, anis and soap. As always with cantillon, the sourness is overpowering. Finish is dry. Overall, this is a good kriek with a nice fruitiness.

Bottle from 2006. A nose of chocolate, liquorish and sugars. Taste is of chocolate, liquorish, tar, coffee and vanilla. Its powerful, a little bit acidic and really bitter. Finish is heavy: Salt, bitterness and a touch of alcohol. This brew is extremely powerful, yet balanced and enjoyable. Too bad this was my last bottle.
A nose of lemons and hops. Taste is of honey, flowers and citrus. Its quite sweet, but also bitter and dry in the finish. A british-style IPA that were probably better a couple of months ago.

A nose of pineapples, pinewood, butter and lemon. Taste is of pinewood, grape, butter, passion fruit and basil. Finish is bitter, a bit soapy and contains a pinch of alcohol. I actually enjoyed this one! good balance, a nice acidity and not too bitter. Very nice!
A nose of pine, lemon, toffee and butter. A taste of soil, lemon, iron and a tiny bit of lightly roasted malts. This brew lacks both bitterness and aromas. Maybe a bad bottle?

A nose of snuff, soil, tobacco, liquorish and a kind of metallic funk that goes away when the beer warms up. Taste is of all the above mentoined plus chocolate, cherries, wood and coffee. Its acidic, a bit dry and not so bitter. I think I can discern a characteristic trait among some of the strong stouts and porters from Scandinavia, such as Hr and Fru Frederiksen, Mikkeller BGB and Ngne  IS. They all share a note of tobacco, and a earthy, funky acidicy that ends in a dry finish. Overall, this is drinkable and a very interesting buy!

A nose of firewood, smoked sausage, iron, some sweetness, and lots of tar. Taste is of roasted malts, iron, smoked ham or sausage and caramel. Some acidicy and bitterness initially, but it is replaced by a distinct smokeyness and a kind of dry character in the finish. The regular mrzen is a bit boring; this Urbock is what its all about! I usually dont like smoked beers, thinking the sweetness dont mix with all the smoke, but this brew is really balanced in that aspect.

A nose of citrusy hops and soap. Taste is of lemon, iron, grass and a tiny bit of yeast. Finish is a little adicic and dry. Some bitterness is decernible. A descent brew, but it feels like brewdog should focus less on image, and more on substance sometimes.

Totally fresh bottle: A faint nose of vanilla, whiskey, chocolate and a bit of metallic funk. Taste is of vanilla, chocolate, metal and a raw note of whiskey, tar and smoke.
Body is a bit thin. Finish is a little acidic, bitter and dry. Alcohol comes through as it reaches room temperature. To sum it up: The bitterness is too present, the notes of whiskey are too hay-like and raw, and the other flavors doesnt quite come out and/or melt together. It probably has to settle down a bit. Just 3 months or so.

A chemical nose of passion fruit and what I percieve as sweetness. A taste of toothpaste, chemical passion fruit and apples. Its sweetish, a bit acidic, minty and with a sticky palate. Not very good (dju dju mango were better) but not as bad as Floris Fraise - I assure you, even though I havent tried that one !
A faint nose of American hops a a tad bready malts. Taste is very weak; grapefruit and cucumber. Finish is bitter. This was a bad bottle. I will rerate!

A nose of tobacco, roasted malts, chocolate and vanilla. Taste is mellow but enjoyable. The chocolate beans and the vanilla gives it a certain flavour... Vanilla, tobacco and olives. A little sweetness and a bit dusty. Finish is roasted, with a tad of sourness, then quite dry. This is not outstanding, but its very drinkable. Similar to both Smrpundet and Mikkeller BG Breakfast.

A nose of vanilla, vinegar, oak, and lemon detergent for dish washing. Taste is of oak, apples, metal and funk. Its sweet and a little bit sour. Finish is dry. Hmmm... I dont know what to make of this.

It pours a death metal- black with almost no head. A nose of smoke, chocolate, liquorish and coal. Taste is heavily dominated by raw coffee, but some liquorish, tobacco and tar is there as well. Finish is heavily roasted, salty and bitter. This is a good brew, but its not very complex. The port wine barrel aging isnt really discernible, and those molasses and figs doesnt really come out either.

An aroma of vinegar, funk, wood and cassis. Taste is of blueberries and cassis. Acidic at first, then fruity and dry in the finish. Its elegant and drinkable - the fruity character of those blueberries are really suitable for a fruit lambic!

Aroma is wonderful, kind of similar to Westvleterens 8 and 12. Dough, red wine, blackcurrant and cinnamon. The taste doesnt live up to the aroma, but its still good. Raisins, chocolate, spices, nuts, yeast, soil and dried fruit. Finish is dry and with a little bit of alcohol. This is a truly vinous brew, slightly acidic and with lively carbonation.

A nose of toffee, candy, syrup and soil. Taste is of ruccula-salad, butter, grass, soil and citrus. Bitterness is fairly low, finish is salty and slightly alcoholic. Not a typical DIPA - elegant and drinkable!

A nose of roasted malts, julmust and clove. Taste is of spices, clove, raisins, anis, walnuts and chocolate. Its salty, yeasty, vinous and malty. Finish is alcoholic and dry. There is a slight sensation of metallic bitterness in the taste as a whole. OK, so this is clearly not your typical BW. The strategy is obviously not to brew a subtle, balanced type of beer here, but rather to pack as much taste as you can into the tiny 33 cl bottle. The result is a fairly complex and interesting creation, but the over-the-top mindset is not my cup of tea when it comes to these types of brews. As with North Coasts Brother Thelonious, a heavy taste of fermented raisins paired with a robust sweetness makes this beer less enjoyable than it might have been if the brewers held back a little.

A very complex and wonderful nose of dough, plums, chocolate and alcohol. Taste is of nuts, raisins, dried fruit, yeast, sugars and marzipan. Finish is pretty alcoholic. Maybe I should have aged this a bit longer - sampled young this is a good abt, reminicent of the 8, but the alcohol and the marzipan takes over too much (much like the young quad from La Trappe). For now, I have to say that the 8 is better.

A nose of pear, yeast, lemon and alcohol. Taste is of pear, lemon, butter and grass. Finish is dry, alcoholic, bitter and salty. A pretty good blonde belgian strong. A bit too alcoholic to be truly enjoyable, though.

A nose of coffee, liquorish and whiskey. Taste is of coffee, green olives and chocolate. Its a bit smokey and roasted. This is a dry, light-bodied porter, with very little sweetness and alcohol. Elegant and very drinkable!
